title: Some Good Omens headcanon
body:
I saw Good Omens, and I have headcanon, which I, surprisingly, have never seen yet, but in my opinion it fits perfectly with the story. Imagine Crowley and Aziraphale celebrating the liquidation of Armageddon at the Ritz. Imagine after the words “none of this would’ve worked if you weren’t a little bit a good person… and if you weren’t enough of a bastard” they eat for a while, and then Aziraphale says, “Actually, it’s amazing.”
“What?” Crowley asks. “That it has worked?”
“No. I mean, yes. I mean… that we were able to move away from what we were meant to be.”
Crowley just raises an eyebrow, waiting.
Aziraphale clears his throat. “I mean, angel and demon. Good and evil. Destiny. All that. We’ve become more than that. We started to work together, understand each other and people. We shouldn’t have. None of our people did.”
“Well, we just chose who to be,” Crowley shrugs.
“Exactly!” Aziraphale exclaims fervently. “We chose! Free will, like people. Was it given to angels and demons? Because I definitely feel like I have it.”
“Yeah,” Crowley snorts. “Tell me you ate an apple, too.”
Aziraphale flinches and looks away. Crowley notices that the tips of his ears have turned pink, and suddenly it reminds him very much of that distant day when they stood on the wall of Eden and the angel confessed that he gave his flaming sword to Adam and Eve. The demon straightens up in his chair, looking at Aziraphale with admiring disbelief.
“No,” he exhales. “You didn’t.”
“I didn’t rip it off!” Aziraphale says desperately. “It was already laying on the ground!”
“No way. I can’t believe it,” Crowley grins involuntarily. “You ate it.”
“I was in frustrated feelings! I had just given away my sword and wondered if I had done the right thing or not. And there it was… so beautiful, so red. I thought since it fell itself, there would be no harm, and I just… Wait.” Confusion appears on the angel’s face and then gives a way to suspicion. “What do you mean ‘too’? Did you?..”
Crowley, already recovered from his surprise, leans back in his chair.
“Of course I did. I’m a demon. And I’ve already told you what I think about the ban on apples from a tree which grows in the most accessible place and which lacks only a neon sign.”
“Oh my God,” Aziraphale says in an unhappy voice. “Oh, my God. So we really… have more free will than other angels and demons?”
“It may be so. Who knows, maybe the Ineffable Plan foresaw this?”
“Who knows…” Aziraphale echoes.
He still seems a little scared and unsure, glances up at the ceiling as if he’s about to be struck by lightning released by God himself, but clearly begins to calm down. Crowley watches as he picks his fork in his cake, and can’t help but smile, then lowers his head to hide it. Just think, six thousand years of knowing each other, and Aziraphale could still hit him to the depths of his demon soul. Ate an apple, really!
Well, perhaps the next six thousand years, they will not be bored as well.
